UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393288900037
AB  - The paper contains tests of the relation between money and output implied by a real business cycle model. The tests control for a variety that may affect economic growth and the growth rates of monetary aggregates. Using U.S. data from 1953:1–1984:4, we find almost no evidence that the empirical relations between real growth and measures of monetary policy violate the restrictions imposed by the model. Changes in a set of real variables explain a majority of the variation in GNP growth. However, substantial variation in GNP growth remains unexplained by the real factors that we consider.
